<h1>
    HTTP Methods – Introduction
</h1>

<hr>

🔹 What are HTTP Methods?
1.HTTP Methods are used to define what action we want to perform on the server data
2.Whenever we call an API, we must specify what we want to do
3.These methods are part of the HTTP protocol

Simple understanding:

👉 HTTP Method = Instruction to the server

Example:
1.If you want data → use GET
2.If you want to add data → use POST

🔹 Why HTTP Methods are Important

1.They tell the server what type of operation to perform
2.Without methods, server will not understand your intention
3.They make APIs:
    A.Structured
    B.Predictable
    C.Easy to use

🔹 Common HTTP Methods

🔸 GET (Read Data)
1.Used to fetch data from server
2.Does NOT modify any data
3.Most commonly used method

Example:
GET /users

👉 “Give me all users”

Key Points:
1.Safe (no data change)
2.Idempotent (same result every time)
3.Used for displaying data

Real-world examples:
1.Loading Instagram feed
2.Fetching product list
3.Getting weather data

🔸POST (Create Data)
1.Used to send data to server
2.Creates new resource

Example:
POST /users

👉 “Create a new user”

Key Points:
1.Data is sent in request body
2.Not idempotent (creates new entry every time)

Real-world examples:
1.Registering a user
2.Submitting a form
3.Placing an order

🔸 PUT (Update Data)
1.Used to update existing data completely

Example:
PUT /users/1

👉 “Update user with id 1”

Key Points:
1.Replaces entire data
2.Idempotent

Real-world examples:
1.Updating profile details
2.Editing product info

🔸DELETE (Remove Data)
1.Used to delete data from server

Example:
DELETE /users/1

👉 “Delete user with id 1”

Key Points:
1.Removes resource
2.Idempotent

Real-world examples:
1.Deleting account
2.Removing item from cart

